To make the right decision is a key. While some people only need to have a “gut feeling” or base their decision on their best guess, others want to rely on something more tangible and exact.

Data science provides an answer for the latter. Daily, large amounts of “big data” are collected from countless sources and for various purposes. Why not take an advantage of that? Correct use of databases and relevant data, together with an access to the right tools and skills such as SQL or R backs up managerial decision with real-life and up to date information, maximizing the chance of making the right decision.

I have based my choice to study Marketing Intelligence on a desire to positively impact companies and directly contribute to the bottom line. skills: ['Statistics', 'R (Programming Language)', 'R', 'Higher Education', 'Learning Analytics', 'Research', 'Spreken in het openbaar', 'SPSS', 'Organisational Behaviour', 'Psychometrics', 'Overleaf', 'LaTeX', 'Latent GOLD', 'General Data Protection Regulation (GDPR)', 'AVG', 'Research Data Management', 'FAIR Principles', 'Policy Compliance', 'Social Psychology', 'Regression Discontinuity Design']
summary:
I work as a researcher, data steward and researcher at the Methods & Statistics unit of the faculty of Pedagogical and Educational Sciences.

My current roles:

● I am a lecturer in the course Inferential Statistics, which is offered to both premaster students (Feb + March) and bachelor students (April + May), respectively.

● As a data steward, I am responsible for the storage of research data (adherence to FAIR principles) and ensuring GDPR (EU privacy law) compliance in scientific research conducted at the institute.

● My research is focused on two key projects:

- Learning Analytics – I develop learning analytics to gain insights into study progress. As an example, I try to understand the learning trajectory in nongraded, formative quizzes through process variables such as duration, login time, and quiz grades.

- Psychometrics – I use simulated data to better understand how statistical models answer research questions relevant to psychological science. As an example, I simulate experience sampling method data that fits analyses with Multilevel Regression Model and with Multilevel Latent Markov Models to uncover when both analyses can best be applied.


Ambition:

I am currently seeking a PhD position starting this summer, and would be delighted to hear from anyone who feels my expertise and research interests would be a good fit for their team. Please feel free to reach out to me at your convenience.

Analytical techniques I have used and/or studied:

- Dynamic Network Models
- Discrete Latent Variable Models (e.g., Latent Class Analysis, Latent Markov Models)
- Multilevel Regression (e.g., Cross-Sectional and Repeated Measures)
- Continuous Latent Variable Models (e.g., Exploratory and Confirmatory Factor Analysis)
- Multiple Machine Learning Techniques (e.g., k-fold Cross Validation)
- Structural Equation Models
- Meta Analysis
